Base Titanium mining company, has transformed lives of Kwale residents through projects, the Vision 2030 Delivery Board has said. Chairman James Mwangi on Monday said the firm has improved residents’ living standards in less than five years. He presented a certificate of recognition to the firm. A 2016 survey by Ernst and Young showed Base Titanium supports 1,360 jobs through the consumer-supplier chain. The firm supports farming, offers scholarships and invested Sh7.6 billion directly in community projects. “Base Titanium has created employment opportunities and prioritised the community. The firm will help alleviate poverty,” Mwangi said. The company has created 3,400 jobs — 624 are direct jobs, with 96 per cent of employees being Kenyans. Kwale residents have benefitted from 64 per cent of direct jobs.